<br>
As a user of a Velk robe, I can attest that it makes a huge difference in exp grind groups and even high hp mobs. I still do not do as much damage as tanks (see his analysis above which is very good by the way) but I do enough damage to make me an addition to an exp group.<br>
<br>
At the end of the day, you take exp from a group, every class in the group has to make the group as a whole kill more mobs than they would without you and at least enough to make up for the exp you are taking.<br>
<br>
That is the basic premise of group desirability. Thus the desire of chanters and clerics because they speed up the pulls considerably and make up for even more than their share of exp they cost the group. By having a velk robe, my damage output speeds up the groups pulls to at least cover myself and sometimes a bit more.<br>
<br>
As the higher end game progresses, utility slots just cost too much in the way of maximizing exp so many groups go without an evaccer or utility slots. This holds true for all classes, not just wizzys. Anyone that does not make a group kill at least 1/6th more mobs over a given time, if they are the 6th member, are not necessary and will not be in groups.<br>
<br>
I like the idea of clickable items with decent cast times at all levels. Adding 35 dps to a 55-60 wizzy over their normal damage does not seem unbalancing given the DPS of other PCs and the limitations of a casting item (see above)<br>
<br>
For instance, making the casting time of the quest robes (enticement of flame 360 damage) a 10 second cast increases DPS by 36 but only if in a constant ngagement situation. I think it is fair and reasonable.<br>
<br>
As for the lower level items, just find out what the average DPS of warriors, monks, and rogues are. Compare to DPS over the long haul of the wizzy, then put an item in game that adjusts accordingly (just under warrior, monk, rogue)<br>
<br>
As far as sustained damage, that is what pets bring to other classes that make them desirable. A pet supplies the same damage that our click items would. Wizards are the only non pet caster group and during the original forging of the &quot;vision&quot; I think they underestimated people's innate desire to maximize gain vs. time and it would translate into desirability in groups.<br>
<br>
We will see what the &quot;vision&quot; holds. I am sure they did not realize that a 30 second cast time on a combat spell was a little silly and has absolutely NO use.<br>
<br>
Fasty <p></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub23.ezboard.com/ufastasia.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Fastasia</A> at: 1/3/02 8:14:53 pm<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#33333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub23.ezboard.com/ugrimstafftheurgist.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Grimstaff Theurgist</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Forum Sorcerer</span><br>  Posts: 4111<br> <font color=#ffffff>(1/3/02 10:15 pm)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> no use?</span><hr size=1> &quot;We will see what the &quot;vision&quot; holds. I am sure they did not realize that a 30 second cast time on a combat spell was a little silly and has absolutely NO use.&quot;<br>
<br>
Exactly how could this escape the attention of anyone this side of a striped-ass baboon?  Seriously, that's a clear and obvious truth, they didn't mean for this to make combat impact, they threw it in for us to have something to do with no mana - then made it so you can't meditate while its casting, negating its value. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#000000><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub23.ezboard.com/ucassiusruneblaze.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Cassius Runeblaze</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Forum Sorcerer<BR>I <3 Zealots</span><br>  Posts: 739<br> <font color=#ffffff>(1/3/02 10:20 pm)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Fixing wizards: my recommendations (long)</span><hr size=1> <br>
Well I certainly agree with most everything here. Its what I've been saying for a while, but never put the effort in to present such a well constructed argument. I take my hat off to you.<br>
<br>
With regards to simply lowering nuke costs, I'm a little warey. One of the distinctions of the wizard class is its ability to provide very fast dmg, and whilst you argue its useless, I'd argue it merely marginalised to an extent it appears useless. I would prefer they went the higher damage route as it prevents us from merely becoming second rate warriors or monks who stand further back and spam spells/robes non stop forever trying to chase max dmg.<br>
<br>
To wit, I want aggro to remain a governing factor. This has one beautiful side effect, as your guild/group mates become better equiped, you are able to scale with it and produce more dmg output as they will be better able to keep aggro. For this to work, we need to be able to do more damage in less time if we so choose, which I believe was the original balance goal.<br>
<br>
This leads onto another point, contrary to popular opininon, its really hard to deliver damage at maximum efficiency as a wizard especially on long uber mob fights where we are meant to excel. Concussion simply doesn't work against the majority of these mobs, and the number of times I've been quadded for 1000 when the main tank goes down because I've been trying to maximise dmg is unpleasantly high. If our dmg was more balanced, I don't doubt we'd notice this more. My point? That concussion is inadequate, we need something nearer evade in utility - spell casting subtlety is too little and too late. Or better yet we need an accross the board cut in aggro.<br>
<br>
Going onto the medding whilst standing topic, this is interesting as its predicated on whether or not horses are intended to have that behaviour, and following on from that whether they did it through desire, or 'oh shit we don't have a horse sitting animation'. It would certainly make a nice arch or class skill and actually would in some ways be in line with (un)holy steed as it wouldn't give a speed boost, but would work in all zones. I almost dismissed the suggestion at first, but then remembered the essential point. A wizard using clickey items doesn't tend to sit and med much anyway. Optimal use of the orb of torrefaction/vp robe/velk robe all require you to always use it if you aren't at full mana, and insert nukes as your clarity fueled regen permits. So in effect it lessens the value of the items, but ups the value of nukes as you can cast them more often. (Remember items tend to have superior ratios to nukes, but only if you aren't at full mana as they cast so slowly).<br>
<br>
I may have more thoughts on this tomorrow, but I hope some of this is well enough considered to be of use.<br>
<br>
