You are not the first to comment on the poor quality of the color choice for the web graphs.  I would strongly encourage you to download the excel worksheet for actual analysis. The graphs are easier to discern, and you can play with the source data and controls to play with other solutions.  I know, for example, that for your melee balancing work you produced a simulation for modeling melee damage which could probably be used for supplying better raw dps numbers than especially my interpolated values. However, the spreadsheet itself without the exposition is a bit, erm, overwhelming, so the two kind of need to go together.<br>
<br>
The text is a bit rough (I mis-spell separate 43.6% of the time <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :lol --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/laugh.gif ALT=":lol"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> ), but the essense is there and reflects almost all my thinking on the subject. For other, very insightful views on the subject, direct people to this thread, and for the thinking and numbers behind my research, view the class balance thread referenced in the document. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#33333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub23.ezboard.com/ugallenite.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Gallenite</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Forum Wizard</span><br>  Posts: 132<br> <font color=#ffffff>(1/3/02 11:49 pm)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Fixing wizards: my recommendations (long)</span><hr size=1> Apologies for taking up board space with this, but, dumb question:<br>
